5 Types of Flat Iron Waves✨ 

Classic Wave💕 Rotate iron under. This creates less volume at the root. Insert then rotate Iron half turn and slide down

Beachy Wave💕 Do exactly the same as classic except as you reach the ends start to unwind so that ends are more elongated and straighter towards the ends

Bouncy Wave💕 Rotate iron over. This creates more volume at the root. Keep iron horizontal and slide slow and steady for a bouncy volume wave

Diagonal Wave💕 Start iron rotating over and tilted on a diagonal. Create a wave then move down and insert under and change your diagonal to the opposite side. Continue this pattern for a beachy bend

Horizontal Wave💕 Start iron rotating over and hold it horizontal. Rotate your wrist up and down as you slide down the hair to create chic motorcycle waves

3 Ways to make hair grow faster:

1️⃣ 5 min Scalp Massage every day!  This will increase blood flow to your scalp, enhance the strength of your roots, and help nutrients get to your follicle faster, not to mention decreases stress!  The added bonus here is no product is necessary and decreasing stress is the BEST way to increase hair growth at the scalp. Try this on dry hair at night before bed. 

2️⃣ Use a heat protectant EVERY TIME you use hot tools!  Keeping what you already have is essential to getting long and strong hair!  My best tip is to get in a habit of spraying in a detangling spray that has heat protectant in it. That way your strands are ALWAYS protected and you get the added treatment benefit.
For med-thick hair try IGK Good behavior spray. If you have fine-thin hair try Amika the Wizard spray.(linked in bio)

3️⃣ Brush hair gently!  How you brush your hair matters. Treat you hair like a delicate fabric. Start in the ends of your hair and go slow and steady. 
My fave detangling brush is by Ergo. It’s the gentle paddle brush, linked in my bio.

Do this instead⬇️

Having healthy hair is all about creating healthy habits!

✅Do always prep hair with a detangling spray. As a bonus it treats hair and protects against heat damage. 
✅Do dry hair with a microfiber towel. This creates less tension on the hair line. 

✅Do ALWAYS use heat protectant spray before using any heat styling tools

✅Do always make sure hair is 100% dry before using curling or flat irons. 

✅Do make sure hair is dry before pulling into tight styles. Hair stretches most when wet. This can cause breakage and pull at your scalp. 

✅Do use a scalp scrub brush every time you shower. Bonus points if you massage your scalp before getting in the shower! 

✅Do detangler and brush hair before showering. This ensures easier detangling after showering. Treat your hair like a delicate fabric. 

Start doing these healthy hair habits now to have stronger hair later!✨

2️⃣ Section your hair, width of section should be the same as width of curling iron

3️⃣ When curling away from face clamp goes in front of section. When curling toward face clamp goes behind the section. 

4️⃣ As you feed the hair through the iron grab end of hair to keep it smooth

5️⃣ Let cool before touching curls, then use fingers or brush to separate!

Busting these myths to help you ACTUALLY get healthier hair!

1️⃣I’m not sure how this “wash your hair once a week” trend started but I can tell you from watching my own clients scalps change that this needs to stop asap. Think of it this way…would you wash your face once a week?  Although washing out hair every day may not be necessary I would argue that as long as you are using good products with good ingredients it’s better than washing once a week. I think for the average person washing your hair once every 2-3 days is fair. On the days you aren’t washing be sure to brush it at least massage your scalp once a day. 

2️⃣Cold water rinse alone will not do anything special to your hair. Obviously rinsing with super hot water would also not be ideal. Use warm water, more importantly use a hair mask once a week for shinier, healthier hair. 

3️⃣Your shampoo will not get used to your hair but your hair texture might change which means you would need a different shampoo. Or maybe you do a color change going from brunette to blonde or vice versa, that would also mean you would need to change your shampoo and conditioner so that you have the right ingredients to care for your new hair. Generally speaking darker hair needs more moisture and blonder highlighted hair needs more protein-based or  repair type products.

Haircare Tips no one is talking about!

Treatment Styler vs. Styling Products and why YOU might need both💕

Treatment Styler: this product goes into damp hair before blow drying. It usually has heat protection and treats specific hair needs such as frizz, more density, color protection, protein builder etc.  The more you use a treatment styler the better the integrity of the hair will become. It goes into the hair and when shampooed the benefits are not rinsed out.

Styling Product: this product goes into damp hair before blow drying as well. They often have heat protection but not always. They help to hold the style of your choice. You can choose to add hold for volume, smoothing, texture, control etc. These products lay on the surface of the hair and when shampooed rinse out completely.

Bonus Info: Finishing products go into dry hair such as hair sprays, texture sprays etc.

The 6 Figure Hairstylist: Have you ever thought you had the BEST week EVER only to receive your paycheck and wonder where the money went?  Keep reading to find out more on how to know your own numbers and FINALLY hit the 100k or higher mark!

$100,000/50wks(accounting for vacation and sick days)
=$2000 a week/4days
=$500 a day

If you make 50% commission you now have $250 a day. Color costs avg is around 8%. This comes off of your total before commission.

$500 x.08 =$40(minus this from your day)
$2000 x.08=$160(subtracted weekly)
$100,000 x.08 =$8,000subtracted yrly)

Taxes are on avg 30%. This comes off of your total, not what you bring into the salon. $100,000 a year after color costs, commission and then taxes now becomes $30,000 a year. This is the number you would see on your yrly tax return. Of course this is not including your tips which would be about 15% on the number you brought in for the year. So $100,000 x15%= $15,000 extra (hidden) income. So now you are back up to almost hitting 50k for the year.

It’s important to understand that what we think we are making is NOT what we are actually making. What you can see you can manage. What you cannot see manages you. What’s the actual number you need to hit to bring in 100k a year? $220,000

$220,000/50 wks
=$4,400 a week/4 days
=$1,100 a day
$1,100 x.08(color charges) =$88 x4 days
=$352 x50 weeks
=$17,600 a year
$220,000/2 (commission or cost of running your business)
=$110,000 -$17,600 (color costs)
=$92,400x.30(taxes)= $27,720
=$67,680 a year after taxes
Plus tips (15%avg) on $220k
=$33,000

$67,680 (tax return)
+$33,000 (tips)
=$100,680 total

***Hot Tip: if your salon offers retail incentive then you can off set your “color charge” by being reimbursed on retail sales. Most salons give 10% of their sales in retail back to them in their pay. If you are selling 10% of your total income then your tax return number would be bigger!  For instance, 10% of 100k is $10,000. If you are hitting that number then include that in your calculations or omit your color charge.

So what was my inspiration for creating this video?  Well I’m so glad you asked…

I actually created this video after explaining and teaching my assistants how holding their curling iron can change the outcome of their curls.

When teaching someone to curl the back of a head, for instance, it’s very common for a stylist to hold the iron the same way they do on the right side of the head as the left…

However, when you do NOT switch your iron placement the curls would in fact appear different NOT the same.  It’s easy to think you will get the same result when you hold the iron the same way but because the head is round, it will not fall the same way.

This video was a way for me to teach and coach for better understanding about how you hold your iron matters.  It’s amazing to think that this “little” video would go on to help stylists and consumers all over the world.

I like to think I’m a tiny tiny part in helping people make small changes that create BIG impact.

The point of this post?  When I created and posted this…I did not expect the VIRALITY that followed…

The lesson I learned, is that, the smallest pieces of information that we assume so many already know, is usually exactly what people want to learn.
